${\footnote Basic File Operations}
+{\footnote 1}
K{\footnote Basic File Operations;}
\pard \plain \brdrb \cf12 \fs24 \b
Basic File Operations\par
\pard \plain \cf0 \fs20
{\uldb Files}{\v 20437}\par
\par
\{bmc IDF20439.bmp\}\tab \b \i new file \i0 \b0 \par
\par
The \b \i new file \i0 \b0 element serves to create a new file. The file name is entered as a text parameter. When no path to the file exists, it will be created. When the creation operation is successful or if the file already exists, the logical validity flag will be returned. Otherwise the invalidity flag is returned, and, at the same time, the {\uldb operation error flag}{\v 20509} is set.\par
\par
\{bmc IDF20440.bmp\}\tab \b \i new folder \i0 \b0 \par
\par
The \b \i new folder \i0 \b0 element serves to create a new folder. The folder name is entered as a text parameter. When no path to the folder exists, it will be created. When the creation operation is successful or if the folder already exists, the logical validity flag will be returned. Otherwise the invalidity flag is returned, and, at the same time, the {\uldb operation error flag}{\v 20509} is set.\par
\par
\{bmc IDF20441.bmp\}\tab \b \i delete file or folder \i0 \b0 \par
\par
The \b \i delete file or folder \i0 \b0 element serves to delete a file or a folder. The file or folder name is entered as a text parameter. A file having the R/O attribute (modification prohibition), and a non-empty folder (containing a file or another folder) cannot be deleted. When the deletion operation is successful the logical validity flag will be returned. Otherwise the invalidity flag is returned, and, at the same time, the {\uldb operation error flag}{\v 20509} is set.\par
\par
\{bmc IDF20442.bmp\}\tab \b \i test of existence \i0 \b0 \par
\par
The \b \i test of existence \i0 \b0 element serves to find out, whether a disk, a file or a folder exists that has been entered as a parameter. If it exists, the logic validity flag will be returned. By entering a disk specification in form of "\b disk:\b0 " only the disk existence in the computer is tested independently on whether the disk contains a medium (e.g. the floppy disk drive). Following the "\b disk:\\\b0 " specification entry (i.e. the disk's ROOT folder) the disk existence including medium presence will be tested. If the access permission to the ROOT of disk is to be tested, then this can be done by the "\b disk:\\*.*\b0 " test.\par
\par
\{bmc IDF20450.bmp\}\tab \b \i file copy \i0 \b0 \par
\par
The \b \i file copy \i0 \b0 element copies a file into a new file. The name of the source file is specified by the {\uldb active file for reading}{\v 20448}, that of the target file by {\uldb active file for writing}{\v 20449}. The target file must not exist (it will not be overwritten). The element returns a logic flag stating the operation success. If the operation is not successful, an invalidity flag will be returned and an {\uldb operation error flag}{\v 20509} will be set.\par
\par
\{bmc IDF20451.bmp\}\tab \b \i file (folder) move/rename \i0 \b0 \par
\par
The \b \i file (folder) move/rename \i0 \b0 element enables to change the name of a file or a folder, or to move them in another folder. The name of the source file/folder is specified by the {\uldb active file/folder for reading}{\v 20448}, that of the target file/folder by the {\uldb active file/folder for writing}{\v 20449}. The target file must not exist (it will not be overwritten). A folder can be moved within the same disk only, a file can be moved between different disks. This element returns a logic flag indicating the operation success. If the operation is not successful, an invalidity flag will be returned and an {\uldb operation error flag}{\v 20509} will be set.\par
\par
\{bmc IDF20642.bmp\}\tab \b \i file list \i0 \b0 (list of files and folders) \par
\par
The \b \i file list \i0 \b0 element finds all files and folders according to a specification entered as a text parameter, and returns their list as a multiline text, in which each line represents the name of one file/folder (without a path). When entering the file searching mask the asterisk convention can be utilized ("\b ?\b0 " denoting an arbitrary character, "\b *\b0 " replacing a character group). Several file masks may be entered, too, individual masks being separated from one another by the semicolon "\b ;\b0 ". If no file mask is specified, all files and folders of an active folder will be searched for.\par
