\pard \plain \cf0 \fs20
{\uldb Files}{\v 20437}\par
\par
\{bmc IDF20508.bmp\}\tab \b \i size of file \i0 \b0 \par
\{bmc IDF20454.bmp\}\tab \b \i attribute R/O \i0 \b0 (read-only)\par
\{bmc IDF20458.bmp\}\tab \b \i attribute ARC \i0 \b0 (archive)\par
\{bmc IDF20455.bmp\}\tab \b \i attribute HID \i0 \b0 (hidden)\par
\{bmc IDF20456.bmp\}\tab \b \i attribute SYS \i0 \b0 (system)\par
\{bmc IDF20457.bmp\}\tab \b \i attribute DIR \i0 \b0 (folder, directory)\par
\{bmc IDF20459.bmp\}\tab \b \i attribute TEMP \i0 \b0 (temporary)\par
\{bmc IDF20460.bmp\}\tab \b \i attribute COMP \i0 \b0 (compressed)\par
\{bmc IDF20461.bmp\}\tab \b \i attribute OFF \i0 \b0 (offline)\par
\{bmc IDF20462.bmp\}\tab \b \i date and time creation \i0 \b0 \par
\{bmc IDF20463.bmp\}\tab \b \i last access date and time \i0 \b0 \par
\{bmc IDF20464.bmp\}\tab \b \i last write date and time \i0 \b0 \par
\{bmc IDF20751.bmp\}\tab \b \i nickname (alias) \i0 \b0 \par
\par
The elements intended for servicing the file parameters use the name definitions of files for reading and writing. When reading an element value this value is retrieved from the file/folder for reading; when writing a value into an element this value is set in the file/folder for writing. If an operation error occurs, the {\uldb operation error flag}{\v 20509} will be set.\par
\par
From among the attributes following attributes only may be set: R/O, ARC, HID and SYS (logic value), whereas following attributes may be read only: DIR, TEMP, COMP and OFF.\par
\par
The "nicknames" (aliases) are alternative multi-lingual file names. Each file can possess beside its normal file name a nickname, too, under which it is presented to the user. This nickname may be different for every language. A file can possess a short name (8 characters), thus making possible to use long names even in systems not supporting long names (older Novell networks, another language version of the operational system, CD-ROM). The nicknames are stored in the \b ALIASES.INI \b0 file, which is located in the same folder as the file/folder. By writing the text into the \b \i nickname \i0 \b0 element the alternative name of the file/folder for writing is recorded according to the program {\uldb language}{\v 20397} active setting. By reading the text out of the element the nickname of the file/folder for reading may be found out corresponding to the active language or corresponding to another nearest language.\par
